ce:section.ce:para:
Structural characterization of B,N:GQDs were done by using TEM and FT-IR. TEM results showed that size of B,N:GQDs ranged between 2 nm–4 nm with uniform size distribution (Fig. 1
                     ). Also, TEM results revealed that amount of BA in synthesis medium did not affect size and size distribution of B,N:GQDs (Fig. 1) (For size distribution, see Figure S1 in supplementary information). These results are in agreement with literature [34–37]. The carbon/graphene quantum dots synthesized by hydrothermal synthesis method under high pressure and high temperature have typically size in the range of 2 nm–4 nm [34–37]. Boron and nitrogen doped carbon quantum dots synthesized by hydrothermal synthesis method by using APBA have the same size as well [34–37]. Also, addition of an extra doping element, and also extra element precursor, did not affect the size range of quantum dots [34–37]. The size of BN:GQDs are determined by synthesis method and due to using hydrothermal synthesis method, 2 nm–4 nm size range was obtained in this study. FT-IR spectra of B,N:GQDs evinced that as the amount of BA increased in synthesis medium, boron penetrated more into quantum dot structure and hydroxyl groups originated from BA dominated surface of quantum dots (Fig. 2
                     , Figure S2). The FT-IR spectrum of purified B,N:GQDs showed that B,N:GQDs had similar bonding characteristics to BA, with few major differences (Fig. 2). Similarity between FT-IR spectrum of BA and FT-IR spectrum of B,N:GQDs showed that B,N:GQDs contained high amount of B–OH bonding. However, FT-IR spectrum of purified B,N:GQDs possessed 4 different characteristic bonds compared to FT-IR spectrum of pure BA, which became more noticeable as BA amount increased in synthesis medium. These 4 peaks, which appeared at 780 cm−1, 925 cm−1, 1030 cm−1 and 1090 cm−1, arose due to formation of B–N bonding and B–C bonding [35,38] [–] [40]. The peak at 780 cm−1 and the peak at 925 cm−1 were attributed to B–N bonding [38,39] and N–B–O bonding [40], respectively. The other two peaks, peak at 1030 cm−1 and peak at 1090 cm−1 were attributed to B–O–C bonding [39] and C–B bonding [35], respectively. These 4 peaks became more intense and sharper as BA amount in synthesis medium increased. These results revealed that, as BA amount in synthesis medium increased, surface of B,N:GQDs were dominated by –OH groups, boron penetrated more into quantum dot structure and therefore boron character in B,N:GQDs increased. It should be noted that FTIR spectrum of boric acid and B,N:GQDs should be similar at some point due to existence of hydroxyl groups on the surface of B,N:GQDs. These hydroxyl groups are bound to boron, and therefore these features causes similarities between FTIR spectrum of BA and FTIR spectrum of B,N:GQDs.

The peak at 325 nm in absorption spectrum of B,N:GQDs became more apparent as the amount of BA in synthesis medium increased (Fig. 4
                     ). This observation provided a clear evidence about origin of the absorption peak at 325 nm; this peak appeared due to boron based differences in coordination environment and became more noticeable as boron amount increased (Fig. 4) [41]. Accordingly, this observation revealed that contribution of the peak at 325 nm to overall absorption spectrum could be controlled by controlling amount of BA in synthesis medium (Fig. 4). In order to have a complete understanding on photophysical properties of B,N:GQDs, emission spectra of B,N:GQD-APBA upon excitation with different wavelengths (λexc = 350 nm and λexc = 400 nm) were recorded (Fig. 5
                     ). Emission properties of B,N:GQDs showed excitation-dependent characteristics (Fig. 5). When B,N:GQD-APBA were excited at λexc = 350 nm, the emission spectrum showed a single peak at 425 nm (Fig. 5). On the other hand, when B,N:GQD-APBA were excited at λexc = 400 nm, the emission spectrum showed a single peak at 485 nm (Fig. 5). Shift in emission wavelength to longer wavelengths upon increase in excitation wavelength is frequently observed in graphene quantum dots [35]. This characteristic emission behaviour is observed due to fact that emission emerging form surface of QDs and emission emerging from core of QDs become prominent at different excitation wavelengths [35]. In this study, the excitation-dependent emission behaviour of B,N:GQDs showed that the core of QDs and the surface of QDs had different structures, which caused shift in emission wavelengths upon changing excitation wavelength. When photoluminescence excitation (PLE) spectra of B,N:GQD-APBA collected at λemms = 425 nm and at λemms = 485 nm were compared, characteristic differences were observed (Fig. 5). The PLE spectrum at λemms = 425 nm lasted until 400 nm, with two major peaks at 230 nm and 360 nm and a minor peak around 260 nm. On the other hand, the PLE spectrum at λemms = 485 nm lasted until 465 nm, with 3 major peaks at 240 nm, 290 nm and 395 nm (Fig. 5). All peaks which belong to the PLE spectrum at λemms = 485 nm were broader compared to the peaks in the PLE spectrum at λemms = 425 nm (Fig. 5). These clear and characteristic differences showed that emission at 425 nm and 485 nm had different origins.
